rComments: you can tell that she loves neuroscience and cares about her students but her lectures are very monotonous and slow. I do like her handouts. rComments: Dr. Ito is an amazing prof with such a kind heart! Going to her office hours really helps, as she takes the time to explain things. It shows how much she cares for her students. She definitely remembers her students, esp if you take initiative and show that you want to learn. Her courses are on the challenging side but doable. Highly recommend!
avoid her and her courses ... she talks really low and she is so boring

Rutsuko clearly cares about her students and wants to see them excel. I loved this class and felt like it was at the core of my studies as a neuroscience major. Its a hard course and you have to put in a lot of work to see the payoff, but C69 is worth taking just for the knowledge you gain. Take advantage of office hrs, she remembers her students.

rComments: Doesn't use anything from lectures, only the handouts. Usually MC are straight from her handouts but the short answer questions (worth 20% of the overall test) is actual application which are a big tougher. Warns students at the beginning just to scare them, but I got an A in this class (I'm a B student)

rComments: Her lectures and structured in a very helpful way, so that students can take the most from it. She is also approachable and friendly.

Fantastic. She's really clear in lectures, her handouts contain the information that you need, and she really wants you to understand and do well. Her exams are short answer, so they require understanding. Take notes in lecture + read her handouts. For lecs that don't have handouts, just take really good lec notes. You can do well if you work hard!

One of the traits that defines Professor Ito is that she truly cares about her students.  Her teaching style is very professional (albeit slightly mechanical), and her exams are written with the express purpose of challenging her students to apply concepts.  Her courses will leave you with the satisfaction that you are learning neuroscience.
